Dark ashy soil with hypocaust tiles in the “hypocaust room”

Phase X: Site abandonment after major collapse dating to the Byzantine period from the CE 4th to 5th c. New drainage systems are installed including that associated with the newly built west precinct wall.

Locus 7 is a layer of dumping beneath locus 5 in the "hypocaust room." The soil excavated was dark grey with a High pottery and plaster content and a lot of marble fragments. The large number of hypocaust tiles in this layer seem to have been dumped here. The soil size was variable and the Munsell color of clean samples with little ash was 7.5 YR 4/2, Brown. This locus covered the extent of the "hypocaust room" and was very similar to locus 8 but contained fewer tiles. Inclusions in this layer were small and medium sized ash, burnt residue, pottery, stones and tiles.
